text: [Music]
uh hi everyone nice thinning daytano
here the internet's busiest music nerd
and it's time for a review of this new
suicide boys album long-term effects of
suffering this is the second official
commercial album from the new orleans
rap duo their last lp saw ruby and scrim
definitively diving into the memphis
inspired sound they had been sailing on
for an ocean's worth of eps and mixtapes
up until that point and the project
overall i thought turned out all right
there were a lot of quality beats and
flows on this thing but not a lot to
write home about on the chorus front on
the songwriting front which was also the
case for a lot of their ep material but
i was hoping because this was an album
that they would get a bit more ambitious
with what they were delivering here and
i went into this new project with mostly
the same hopes for a lot of reasons but
mostly because without anything catchy
baked into the pie a lot of the duo
songs tend to melt together in a
somewhat forgettable way after i want to
die in new orleans suicide boys also
toned down their prolific streak a
little bit focused on some hip-hop and
rock fusions with travis barker on a
little project i thought this might lead
to a shake-up in their sound or
something but the lead-up to this new lp
has been pretty mild this past april
there was the teaser the single new
profile pic which was a song that by
suicide boys standards was so average i
thought this was just going to be like a
random non-album single they sort of
tossed out there to keep fans held over
and remind them that they're still
active after a mostly silent pandemic
year but no this track's actually on the
record and it is so bleh there was also
the single avalon which had more of a
druggy psycho horror core edge to it the
flows on the song feel like a cross
between 3 6 bone thugs and a little bit
of icp and i don't mean that comparison
in a negative way there are a few sick
bars here and there on the track like
snore to 30 off the 40 let it bust but
for every cold lyric here there's a
tacky one too the vibe of the track is
scummy it's dark and it's not really
much else as suicide boys continue to be
allergic to writing memorable choruses
or lyrics that are all that focused much
of the album runs the same with ruby and
scrim giving us one
grim and samey banger after another
granted some of the material is spookier
than usual like the opener or the
amazingly titled if self-destruction
was an olympic event i would be tonya
harding but it's hardly a new and
exciting direction that's not to say
suicide boys don't do anything new on
this project they do but it comes in
spurts life is but a stream seems like a
vague nod to emo trap with its melodic
lead vocals and sparkling guitars but
it's just not a sound i think the duo
executes boldly there's the even worse
five grand 8-1 which is some sleepily
executed jazz rap that gets really stale
really fast then the track forget it
features these really relaxed beats
elastic futuristic synthesizers and
pretty touched up and dreamy vocals it
sounds like a musical
job application to uh you know join the
drain gang or get blade on a feature or
something after these tracks i can kind
of see why suicide boys usually stick to
their guns look there are somewhat
strong tracks in the track list here but
when that's happening it's usually as a
result of the production carrying things
a little bit i love the beat on we envy
nothing in the world but honestly the
simple hypnotic synthesizers and the
booming bass on that one read like
something i could hear cardi just doing
some baby boy over on a whole lot
of red there are even moments on this
project where the rapping isn't even all
that tight the song ugliest for example
this to me sounds like two dudes
nonchalantly riffing over some gloomy
boom bap for
a soundcloud upload which i guess makes
sense given suicide boy's origins but in
that same breath the closer is such a
refreshing change of pace not only
because it has a legit memorable chorus
on it but the lyrics on this one from
front to back come from a really
personal introspective place with a
heavy focus on motivating inspiring
carrying on but there's not a whole lot
else on this record that seems as
thorough or as thought through look at
the end of the day i do find it
admirable that
suicide boys have a sound and an idea
and a vibe in mind for their music and
they just stick to that and they chase
it and regardless of what i think they
do it independently and to an audience
of millions still though that doesn't
change that for me
long-term effects feels way more like a
compilation of
spooky fleeting moments as opposed to an
album of thoroughly conceived songs
feeling a strong four to a light five on
this one tran position have you given
this album a listen did you love it did
you hate it what would you rate it
you're the best you're the best what

like please subscribe and please don't
cry hit the bell as well over here next

suicide boys forever
